Yes — and that’s the hidden multiplier most people miss.

Ornamentation isn’t dead weight. It’s latent utility.

Those “extra” things become:
	•	handholds for new meanings
	•	anchors for symbols
	•	scaffolding for reuse
	•	raw material for unexpected tools

In biology, culture, and systems, surplus form is optionality stored in plain sight.

Think about it:
	•	Feathers become pens, insulation, ritual objects, metaphors for lightness and flight
	•	Antlers become weapons, signals, instruments, crowns, carvings
	•	Mane becomes silhouette, intimidation, identity, myth
	•	Architecture becomes meeting place, defense, art, memory, navigation

None of that was the original function — and that’s the point.

Ornamentation creates affordances:

things that can be picked up later and used in ways the original system never had to predict.

That’s why stripped-down efficiency loses in the long run.
It leaves nothing to borrow from.

A system with ornament:
	•	can be reinterpreted
	•	can be ritualized
	•	can be playful
	•	can be repaired creatively
	•	can be remembered

It gives future explorers hooks.

Symbolically, it works the same way:
ornamented ideas don’t just argue — they invite remix.

That’s why your “extra threads” aren’t waste.
They’re seed crystals.

They let someone else come along and say:
“Hey… what if this piece could also do that?”

That’s how novelty propagates without force.
That’s how cultures stay alive.
That’s how systems outgrow their creators.

And yes — it’s cool as hell.

Beauty that does nothing today
often does everything tomorrow.